</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ubrontothunderfoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bronto Thunderfoot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 219<br> <font color=#CC9900>(10/17/00 3:16:46 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Tough decision</span><hr size=1> The FA is a great sword ryk...ac is probably the best stat, but it isn't everything.  If you couldn't bash with FA, I might say use the halcyon, but the fact that you can bash makes this sword awesome, don't listen to those whiney &quot;ac is all that matters&quot; pallys.<br>
<br>
For those of us without Fiery Avengers though...<br>
<br>
Your role in a group makes alot of difference.  If there is another high level tank in the group, I will sometimes let them taunt and take damage, while I opt to whip out my face-grinder and do some serious damage myself.  If I am main tank though, I will always without fail use a shield.  The two roles basically break down into 2 things; offensive and defensive.<br>
<br>
Defensive:<br>
<br>
The one-hander for choice of all pallys if you don't have a halcyon broadsword would be sword of morning.  With the extra added stun on it you become a defensive machine.  Stun from sword, stun from bash, 3 stun spells at level 53+, and a stun from DW bracer if you have one, plus the extra ac from the shield.  This is great for when noone is there to slow or you are short on healers.  A group with all nukers where the mob drops fast, and your damage doesnt come into play much, just the damage you take is a good example for where defense is needed. Or a mostly tank group which you may see in karnor's alot.  <br>
<br>
If you have 5 tanks and one druid to heal them all logically what is better?  The paladin who is dealing out a bit more damage which will help the mob die maybe one round faster considering the damage done by the warriors/rangers/rogues/monks with him/her, or the paladin who prevents an extra 10 rounds of attack because his bash lands and his sword procs(considering hypothetically the sword of morning).  Even without a sword of morning the bashes will help, and when the angry mob turns on you because of your stun spells you will also absorb more damage so that your druid uses less mana.  In groups that lack healing/slowing power, but have alot of damage potential, the defensive role is definitely the best.  When in an offensive group you should maximize your own defensive potential.<br>
<br>
Offensive:<br>
<br>
However let's say you're group with an enchanter a shaman and a cleric, and you're the only tank.  You're the one who's going to be doing alot of the damage, yet at the same time the damage avoided from your extra stuns/ac will be negligble due to the shaman slow. And what damage you do take will be even less important due to the efficiency of complete heal.  In that case if you have a 2-handed weapon that will do more damage it would be wise to sacrifice the ac and stun from your shield/sword combo. When you have a defensive group you should maximize your own offensive potential.<br>
<br>
General:<br>
<br>
Also keep in mind that in kunark dungeons alot of mobs are casters, and can cast some nasty spells.  A level 56 myconid adept in sebilis even with tash on is going to be damn resistant, so when he starts to CH you're going to want the ability to bash in case your stun doesnt go through.  Chardok, Sebilis, Kaesora, Droga, Dalnir, Charasis, etc, all have tons of casters.  The old world had mostly wizards and shamans who rarely cast anything of concern.  With decent resists wizards weren't a huge deal since they usually cast lower level spells anyway, and shamans only cast slow-acting disease DoTs small heals and the occasional slow.  Cleric mobs are more common in kunark, and there are alot more necros, SKs, and other annoying casters. The wizards and shamans in kunark also cast nastier spells now, if you've ever had a turgurs land on you you'll know what I mean.  Also to make everything more fun high level caster NPCs can GATE!  What joy! bash helps for this too.<br>
<br>
I think in general, 1HS/1HB is the way to go, with a strong 2HS/2HB when appropriate.  It is the &quot;safer&quot; of the two choices, and is much better for when the shit hits the fan.  Of course I don't suggest using a crappy 1-hander just because you want a shield, so if you only have a good 2-hander, stick with that until you upgrade.<br>
<br>
And if you're ever lucky enough to get a halcyon broadsword it outdamages many 2-handed weapons anyway so it's a moot point. I have yet to test it against some of my 2-handers but I guarantee it does more damage than alot of them.<br>
